Scheduled tasks — cron, at, and systemd timers.

Sometimes you don't want to run a command now; you want it to run later, or on a schedule. There are three ways to do that.

The classic is cron, the recurring scheduler. Each user has their own crontab, a table of scheduled jobs. You edit yours with crontab dash-e, and list it with crontab dash-l. A crontab line is five time fields followed by the command to run. Reading the fields left to right: minute, zero to fifty-nine; hour, zero to twenty-three; day of the month; month; and day of the week, where Sunday is both zero and seven. Each field can be a specific number, a range like nine-dash-seventeen, a list like one-comma-fifteen, a step like star-slash-fifteen for "every fifteen," or a bare star meaning "any value." So thirty space two space star star star means daily at two-thirty in the morning. And zero space nine star star one-dash-five means nine AM on weekdays.

Now, cron has three gotchas that bite absolutely everyone, so burn them in. First, cron runs with a minimal environment; its PATH is often just slash-usr-slash-bin and slash-bin, so use full paths to your commands, or your script won't find them. Second, there's no interactive shell, so anything that prompts for input will just hang silently forever. Third, output is thrown away unless you redirect it, so append your output and errors to a log file with the double-greater-than and two-greater-ampersand-one idiom. And the golden rule: test the script by hand first, as the user who'll run it. If it works by hand but fails under cron, it's almost always one of those environment differences.

The second tool is at, for a one-off task at a future time. You pipe a command into at, followed by a time like "now plus one hour." atq lists pending jobs, and atrm removes one.

And the third is systemd timers, the modern replacement for cron on systemd systems, which is almost everywhere now. A timer is a dot-timer unit paired with a dot-service unit that does the actual work. Timers have real advantages: they log to journalctl, so all your output is in one place; with Persistent equals true they catch up on runs that were missed while the machine was off; and systemctl list-timers shows you every timer and when it'll next fire. We cover them fully in module nine. For exam purposes: know cron deeply, and know timers at a preview level.
